solution:
The area of the large rectangle is $(x+7)(x+5)$, and the area of the hole is $(2x-3)(x-2)$. To get our answer, we subtract the area of the hole from the area of the large rectangle. \begin{align*}
(x&+7)(x+5)-(2x-3)(x-2)\\
&=x(x+5)+7(x+5)-2x(x-2)+3(x-2)\\
&=x^2+5x+7x+35-2x^2+4x+3x-6\\
&=\boxed{-x^2+19x+29}.
\end{align*}

rewritten_answer:
 Utilizing DeMoivre's Theorem, we have:

\begin{align*}
\cos 5 \theta + i \sin 5 \theta &= (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta)^5 \\
&= \cos^5 \theta + 5i \cos^4 \theta \sin \theta - 10 \cos^3 \theta \sin^2 \theta - 10i \cos^2 \theta \sin^3 \theta + 5 \cos \theta \sin^4 \theta + i \sin^5 \theta.
\end{align*}
By comparing the real parts, we deduce that:
\[\cos 5 \theta = \cos^5 \theta - 10 \cos^3 \theta \sin^2 \theta + 5 \cos \theta \sin^4 \theta.\]
Given that $\cos \theta = \frac{1}{3}$, we find $\sin^2 \theta = 1 - \cos^2 \theta = \frac{8}{9}$. Thus, we can calculate:
\begin{align*}
\cos 5 \theta &= \cos^5 \theta - 10 \cos^3 \theta \sin^2 \theta + 5 \cos \theta \sin^4 \theta \\
&= \left( \frac{1}{3} \right)^5 - 10 \left( \frac{1}{3} \right)^3 \cdot \frac{8}{9} + 5 \cdot \frac{1}{3} \cdot \left( \frac{8}{9} \right)^2 \\
&= \boxed{\frac{241}{243}}.
\end{align*}

